<Rating>5</Rating>< text>
Sally's Nail Spa is beyond amazing. It's so beautiful inside and the owner, Sally, is very talented and so sweet. I was in a pinch and could only get my nails done on Sunday but unfortunately many nail salons were closed because of the pandemic and lack of business to keep workers employed. I spoke with Sally over the phone who was able to accommodate me that same day and within the hour, and she came into the salon to do my nails! I brought in my neice to get her nails done too, and she even helped out another customer who happened to be in the area after she finished with us. If you are looking for a clean place with talented and nice individuals, this is the place to come. It's a wonderful thing to be able to support our local businesses, especially during a time of need.<//text>

<Date>1503557550165< /Date><Rating>5< /Rating><Review>I walked in earlier this afternoon to the facility in San Pedro with a friend looking for a unit to rent out. I'm not from LA so I was skeptical on what I could find to hold my things for a reasonable price.  We were promptly addressed by a woman named Carla at the counter. She was genuine in her greeting and insisted that had there been any questions that arose that we not hesitate to ask. We had been to other facilities but seeing as this was a pretty big store we had asked if we could take a look at one of the units, hence I wasn't too sure if I was ready to rent one at this facility or even rent a unit at all. Carla was able to relate to us on a personal level and kept her explanations short and to the point. Since I'm from Alaska, I was planning on transitioning over to LA but wanted to make sure I had everything in check for myself. I also was a bit worried with what I need such as extra boxes. Carla reassured me that they happen to have boxes at a decent price as well if I happened to run into trouble needing things to make the haul of the load somewhat better. Carla was very knowledgeable, respectable, helpful, kind, genuine, and not to mention hilarious. Not only did she have us to deal with but all the while busy with answering phone calls and other customers in such a professional manner. March 9th, I arrived to reserve a unit, was recommended storage unit B-12 (1st floor) for the size I was seeking (10x20) by the employee handling my reservation. While inspecting the unit she pointed out issues with the wall and promised that maintenance would resolve that issue and the unit on the other side was vacant. She stressed that my unit would not need to be accessed at all and continued to clarify that my items would be safe and the property has cameras. <UserId.>107493710427096544131<//UserId.><name>Samantha Jogoleff< /name>< date>
1619443842032< /date>
< Rating>

< Text>
My husband and I had heard really good things about this place, but unfortunately we had left town by the time they were reopened from COVID.

During one of our recent trips back to Cali we were randomly in the area as they were opening and knew it was fate that we must try them!

Boy oh Boy we are so glad that we did! At their downtown San Diego location they have over 70 different flavors available that they make in house!!

All of their ice creams are egg free and they even have dairy free options. One cool thing we found out was that the milk they use has a 7 day or less cow to machine time!! That means they use the freshest milk around!! They even use pecans from a local farm and are made fresh just for them! You can tell the owner ‚Äúscoop dog‚Äù takes pride in quality and customer service.

As we were there ordering a ‚Äúregular‚Äù walked in and was inquiring about a custom ice cream flavor she wanted to have created for her husband who would be coming home from the military and she wanted to surprise him with it. The owner said he‚Äôd come up with a special batch just for him! How cool is that?

Because there was so many flavors they have the option to do flights of ice cream... so of course we had to do two flights and a regular scoop.

The flavors we got were as follows:
Bourbon pecan
Give me samoa
Pistachio
Red sky
Kahlua espresso
Graham central station
Key lime
Elvis
Peanut butter salted fudge

First off a regular scoop of ice cream is legit massive!! Probably the same size as a double scoop somewhere! Second‚Ä¶all of his names legit taste as described. The ice creams were all super creamy and had their own unique flavors for each.

Our favorite hands down was the graham central station. It is legit life changing. Its a graham cracker flavored ice cream which is absolutely heavenly and taste like you‚Äôre eating honey graham crackers. Theres even a little crunchy grit from the graham crackers, delicious crunchy honey comb pieces for more honey flavor and bits of chocolate. When you go this is a mandatory flavor that you must get!!

We will definitely have to go back to try more flavors. Take your family or just take yourself and get a flight of ice cream so you can have some fun!!<//Text>

<review>I've been going to Westminster Veterinary Group since 2013 when I adopted a kitten from their sister organization WAGS. I have since moved from the area, but I still make the 20-30 min drive out to them for all of my cats' needs because they are awesome.

Everyone there is incredibly friendly and thoughtful. All of the doctors are kind and take the time to explain everything in easy to understand terms. Currently I make a point to try to see Dr. Rettig as she is so knowledgeable and friendly, but she isn't shy about giving an honest opinion which I really appreciate. It's also easy to make appointments and I get appointment reminders when my cats are due for check-ups and vaccinations. They also have an online store that makes it easy to get prescriptions for medications such as flea meds (and the vet will let me know if I pick one that doesn't seem right for my cat) and then set up recurring deliveries so I don't have to remember to buy them.

I recently went to an appointment for the first time during the pandemic and Westminster Vet had a whole system in place to minimize human contact. I went inside (wearing a mask) to drop off my kitty and then went outside to wait in my car. The vet called me on my cell phone to chat about her recommendations for my kitty, and then the front office staff called to confirm the cost and get approval to move forward. Then I got a text when I could come back inside (wearing a mask) to pay and pick up my kitty. Easy peasy!

It's often challenging to find a good vet, so I'm incredibly happy to have found such a great place with consistently excellent service.</review>< Pics>

<user>112882671010173159258<//user><name>Anthony Woms<//name><date>1542862987595< /date>< Rate>
5</Rate>
< review>
Womble is 100% her manic bitey little self again
After being brought in being according to the ER vets who had her overnight with a guarded poor prognosis from Parvo (PLEASE VACCINATE ON TIME, my laziness"it's just a couple weeks" cost me a suffering puppy and the financial equivalent of a decent used car) I watched daily as my baby went from lethargically lifting head to greet me, to walking to me, to running to me, and the night before coming home running to me and jumping up and doing her shake shake dance.
Besides the fact that they saved my baby, I am so glad I picked Westminster because of some big differencces between them & other local vets I have been to.
#1) I am lucky, I have decent credit and had never needed it.. I got a loan to get THE BEST most intensive care, however...had I not been able to, they had other good options available, that would have also likely been successful, at much lower cost. Most vets "oh she has parvo..this is our protocol" with no discussion or personal plan. I never felt like money was the primary factor in anything Westminster Vetrinary did, I can NOT say that about some other local vets.
#2) Visiting your pet (if you are not intrusive etc) is ENCOURAGED (other 2 clinics..it's never allowed...I find that suspect, and also I feel like your pets morale is boosted by visiting, and any injury or illness is better recovered from when you are emotionally happy) we visited Womble at least twice daily for an hour or so, and I think it made her stay happier, even at her sickest to know that it was never going to be long before mama or papa would be there to hold her.
3) Overall environment.
It's clean. It doesn't smell like a barn or have metal chairs. I also loved wombles isolation icu room. A real little room with blanket nests and a bed and toys (yes you can bring from home, and they will also get blanket and toy from vet) food water , room to get up and walk (or run ..Womble is 7lbs so it was a master suite for her) I REALLY liked that she didn't have to see or hear other animals..
4) Staff. I can't say that there was anyone on staff I didn't like(I usually can find someone to dislike lol) everyone seems like they are really at the job they want to be at. I had the most interaction with Sebastian the Vet assistant who was Wombles main human for most of the stuff, he was incredibly knowledgeable about everything (full veterinarians were always accessible, and would call with update/come see me at visits) and he spent a lot of time with Womble and made her toys and he really loves animals/his job/has great people skills too. Both vetrinarians were wonderful. I brought Womble in with an hour notice, from a vet that gave her below 30% survival. Dr Tran came in, and said"I cannot guarantee that she will survive yet, but I practiced in Texas, where we have a lot of parvo puppies (I have spent time in Texas, this is true) I have an 80-90% success rate, Womble is otherwise healthy, she should be able to get through this fine" She also went over the other much cheaper options that still had a very good chance. She was friendly and happy and approachable and got on the floor with Womble and just the same feeling that I got from everyone there... working in Vetrinary medicine is what she does because it's what she wants to do, money is not a driving factor.
I will stop my essay now...but really I cannot say enough good things about you guys. Womble is sleeping happily after attacking her cat brothers and sisters and running and jumping and doing her shake shake dance and eating all day.10 days ago she was so sick we thought she might die on the way to the vet. The treatment for parvo is not fun for the puppy, but they made it as happy and comfortable as possible. For the humans too
And Dr Hueston sorry I didn't mention you, but you were great too, and always on top of it with updates.</review>

<text>After going through a few different vets, we finally found a good place. The place i was going to prior was just after money and nearly left my dogs leg disfigured because they casted it wrong, but luckily we caught onto what was happening. Everytime we come in, the staff is very friendly and welcoming, they greet my dogs like they were their own (my dogs are quite fine with this, it actually puts them at ease). The doctors: Dr. Hueston and  Dr. Tran are very knowledgable and take the time to go over every detail and let me ask as many and whatever questions i have so i have an understanding. They are honest about pricing and procedures. For instance, one of my dogs has been dealing with a foxtail in his leg for awhile now and they lanced it and tried to flush it out the best they could, but unfortunately it didn't get all of it. Instead of doing the procedure over and over again with no avail, they referred me to a specialist because they didnt feel it right to continue to do procedures over and over again if it wasnt working (he had 2  procedues prior from a different vet who claimed it was a tumor, which it wasnt). I appreciate their honesty and will continue to bring my dogs here.<//text><pics>None< /pics>< Resp>

< review>
Dr Greenberg is one of the most respected vets in the country and for good reason.

I am shocked at the bad reviews. It leads me to believe that the money may have been more of an issue to you than your pets welfare. I have never experienced a test that I felt was unnecessary. I hate forking out money but I do it without consideration for the welfare of my kids. Just ask my Care Credit Card.
This is one of the few vets around that cares about the animals and not the money. But realize this is a business and without money they cannot function.

The front desk, most Techs and the Vets know myself and my wife by first name and every single pet we have, Koda, Renji, Skittle-butt, Nani, Scruffy, Toffee and Charmin. How many Vets do you see who need to look at a chart just to remember your name? and still pronounce it wrong. I have even had calls from Dr Greenberg just to see how my kids are doing.

I have nothing but respect for Westminster Veterinary Group and you will be doing your pet a great favor by trusting them.<//review>

< review>
I can't really speak to the competence of the doctors, as I've only had one short visit with them. However, the office is very disorganized, with seemingly no communication happening between the admin staff and the doctor. The admin staff seems, at best, apathetic and inattentive.

Examples:

I answered an extensive questionnaire via an online portal before my appointment. When I arrived, I answered the exact same questions on a paper form. When I met with the doctor, I handed him the completed questionnaire, which he ignored and proceeded to ask me all the same questions a third time while he completed a form on his laptop.

They did not have the proper cable to adjust my travel CPAP, which was the reason I had made the appointment in the first place.

The doctor referred me to a CPAP service center to get the adjustment done. When I went back to the front desk, they had no idea what I was talking about, and tried to make adjustments to my normal (not-for-travel) CPAP, despite having told them multiple times that it did not need adjustment.

When asked when I wanted to schedule my next appointment, I asked for 4 months out. They told me their schedule isn't available that far in advance.

The doctor told me I would be asked to sign a document approving transfer of records from my previous sleep clinic. The admins didn't do this either. I remembered this after getting in my car and leaving, so I drove back to fill out the form.

None of this instilled a sense of confidence in the quality of care provided by the clinic. I've heard the Los Gatos location might be better, so I will schedule my next appointment there. If it doesn't prove to be any better, I'll look elsewhere.<//review>

<Review>Dr. Liebenthal was very thorough in my examination and adjusting the CPAP. She is thoughtful and reviews all facets of my sleep apnea.  She motivates me to continue to try my equipment and instructed me on how to make adjustments . I know she and the team are attentive to my process with the slow Medicare equipment providers.   Follow up visit today was again very thorough - they invited my husband to sit it and she carefully explained her analysis and thinking about my process.  It is always a pleasure to return to a visit with Dr. L.  In her specialist field of sleep apnea  -  she is confident in her knowledge and very comfortable to talk to and does not act hurried. Although I am almost a geriatric,  I would like to say that is as thorough and kind as many pediatricians I have had experienced with younger patients such as my children when they were younger. She is concerned that the patient fully understands the process and very thorough, encouraging and supportive.  Definitely the doctor to choose if you need a sleep apnea specialist who is caring as well as medically experienced.   Dr. Liebenthal  is the best of the sleep apnea specialists I have visited over the years and one of the best doctors I have over decades. <name>Charles Bohe< /name><Date>1620882812108< /Date><Rate>5< /Rate><review>We started our evening at Philippe the Original for their double dip French sandwiches. The sandwiches were excellent with the meat cooked perfectly. One aspect that was nice about Philippe The Original is that there was plenty of free parking, a real treat in LA. Even with the Covid precautions we were able to go in and find an empty booth at about 7PM. May be a little crowed during peak meal times. The dill pickle was excellent. The potato salad had chopped dill pickles added which created a marvelous taste.<//review>< pictures>

< review>
This is one of LA‚Äôs gems, they‚Äôve been here longer than some of the buildings in downtown! Serving sandwiches since 1908, you have to give em a try. Today I had the turkey dip, but I‚Äôm a fan of the beef dip too! I hear the NY pastrami is one of their signatures as well and don‚Äôt forget to ask for extra dip, cause who doesn‚Äôt like soggy bread?! I also added some Swiss cheese just to add some other flavors. I snagged a pickle but I have yet to try their other sides, though they were well dug into, so I‚Äôm sure they‚Äôre just as good. Fun lunch spot, they have indoor and outdoor seating. Indoors is a cute little lunch hall style room with a snack bar on the way out in case you need something sweet to end with because their sandwiches are so savory. They even have a house mustard that comes highly suggested. Definitely enjoy this little trip to the past as it‚Äôs still counter service only and historic memorabilia all over, they still take great pride in their service to LA.</review>

Marissa ‚ÄúMari‚Äù Nicole< /Name>

<text>Philippe's is an amazing place with a ton of history. They also have claim to be the inventor of the French dip sandwich, which has been contested by another LA staple institution- Cole's! Anyhow, I ordered a pastrami French dip(wet) with potato salad and a pickled egg! Whatever you do- don't deny yourself the pleasure of a pickled egg. Their potato salad was spot on and their French dip was to die for. At the mere mention of it, I can feel myself salivating. For those who enjoy an extra kick to their meals, order a small side of horseradish sauce- it'll flare up your nostril and char your taste buds, but it burns soo good! They also have a great beer and wine selection! In regards to parking, they have a large lot, and I have never had any difficulty finding a spot; the location recently opened up dine-in! They've come a long way and if you're tired travel coming in from Union Station, make the walk and have a bite. You won't regret it.< /text><user_name>Hugo Aguas</user_name><userid>116628034618659398361<//userid>< Resp>

An LA classic who is handling the pandemic as well as they can. Very specific protocols in place for distancing and separate entrance and exits to help with flow of foot traffic. They even added outside dining with security to help with any crowd control. Food is as good as I remember, but it‚Äôs been a while and the bread seems smaller but meat ratio better for it. I good trade off from my perspective. Tried the beef, lamb and pastrami to split with my GF. All delicious. Service was a little slower due to changes in the process, I think, so be prepared. Not bad, just have to go to the back for different items. All in all worth the trip to downtown LA for a taste of a classic.<//text>

< UserId.>
116756459050303819481<//UserId.>
<user_name>R Zee< /user_name><time>1620550641618<//time>< rating>
5<//rating>
< review>
Just on atmosphere alone, ya gotta luv this place.  Sawdust on the floor, a whole wall of model trains and artwork/posters from the 20s &30s.  Ya almost expect Hepburn & Tracy to be sitting in the booth next to the one you take.  Now, almost everyone goes there for their "famous" French dip sandwiches, and they are good, real good.  However, they've got some unheralded gems that keep me comin' back.  Their beef stew is awesome....filled with beef, potatoes, carrots, celery and onions, it's as good as what mother made.  And her beef stew was the best thing she made.  The best part tho...before the pandemic, it was $4.25 a bowl(give or take a quarter).  Not a cup, a BOWL.  Their cole slaw is great(yeah, I know what yer thinking, cole slaw??)  It's reeaally good.  Then to top it off, I defy anyone to find a better restaurant slice of banana cream pie than Philippe's.  However, all that said, I gotta admit I was there for the time in about 15 months last week and almost everything was as good as I remember, but the stew was overloaded with too many potatoes and not enough beef.  Turned into soggy mashed potatoe mush by the time I got half way thru.  Hopefully that one time was only an aberration.<//review>

<Gmap_id>0x80c2c65b315cd377:0xa05d997b42357a5</Gmap_id>< text>
You can't go wrong at Phillippe's. One of the best dipped sandwich shops in Southern Cal. The aesthetics of the traditional ambiance is a bit hindered by the structural precautions taken in preparation of the covid pandemic. There is still outdoor dining while the percentage rule is in place for indoor dining. I could be wrong and maybe it's just a matter of getting older, but I visit at least twice a year since I was around 15 years old, and I distinctly remember the lamb tasting a bit gamey back then, better I think, and now seems more tamed as far as flavor is concerned.
I added camera shots of the menu taken 3/30/21

Learn to pronounce</text>

<pics>None< /pics>< text>
They are handling the pandemic beautifully. You order your food and pick it up inside. They're very quick about it. You can get it to go, or eat outside. Tables and a huge canopy are set up behind the restaurant, and it's easy to social distance... plenty of space between tables. A well-dressed, masked server was available outside, prepared with napkins, ice water, utensils, condiments and other things you might need. It was a good feeling. The beef dip was excellent! Good prices, too.<//text>

My first time visiting and it was great!  Lines moved quickly and staff was friendly. There's community seating and if you like your privacy, you can take up a booth.
Loved every bite of my NY Pastrami sandwich! It had a generous serving of pastrami and the French bread was just right.  I had the dip put on the side,  so I can dip top my liking. My side of potato salad was very flavorful and the lemonade was just right,  not too sour or sweet.
Don't forget to get your side of little yellow peppers if you want to spice it up.<//review>

<UserId.>115052272177932580404<//UserId.>< user_name>
Lena Van<//user_name>
<time>1611552642752< /time>< rate>
5<//rate>
<Review>Historic LA eatery that's worth a visit to at least once in your life! Many establishments offer beef dip sandwiches on the menu but very few can claim to be the progenitor of the dish.  Philippe is one of the top contenders and I can say with great confidence that they are very deserving of the title!

They offer a large variety of sandwiches and sides,  all of which are very good. Everything off the menu is always fresh and very tasty.

Ambience is very cozy,  there's lots of knick knacks around and the restaurant space occupies a two story building,  there's lots of nooks and crannies.

Parking is nightmarish 95% of the time,  but that's because it's LA. Thankfully the location is a short walk from Union Station, Oliveira Street,  or China Town.  So pick your spot and walk!< /Review><Pics>None<//Pics><Resp>None< /Resp><gmapID>0x80c2c65b315cd377:0xa05d997b42357a5< /gmapID></record></dataset><record>

<review>I had heard a lot about this place, mostly because it had been around for quite a while. It has a good amount of parking and is open late than most places in Chinatown. A big plus is that you get the food rather quick, which is good. I was fortunate to come when it wasn't so busy although I have heard they tend to have crowds. I tried the beef dipped french dip sandwich since that's what its mostly famous for. To be honest... it wasn't amazing. It was good, but it was lacking that wow factor. I felt with other ingredients, it could be definitely a lot better tasting. It was my first time coming and I do want to try it again, since I feel next time I'll be more in tune with the menu, and perhaps I can make a combination that I feel would redeem that wow factor for this place. For now, it still stands a good place to come at least once, with plenty of choices, seating, clean restrooms and good service, I think I will definitely come back.< /review>< Pics>

< Text>
A Los Angles institution.  This is one of those places that you just have to try once, when you visit LA.  I think I've seen it featured on the Food Network a while back as well.  Philippe specializes in "french dipped sandwiches", of which there are several varieties.  My favorite is the turkey dip.  They also have a wide variety of other choices and even serve breakfast in the morning (never tried it).

I just ate there the other day after almost 20 years and it's still the same great quality as it was back then.  Great place!</Text>

<rating>4<//rating>< Text>
Came here while running around downtown LA! I was surprised because you order and get your food at the same time in parallel with around 10 other customers and the food is carved out for you!

Food: I got the beef dip sandwich double dipped and with French roll. I was pleasantly surprised by how standard these ingredients were but how well it all worked together. There was a nice juicy texture and each bite had me wanting more.

Service: Nonstandard ordering where you go up to the front and ask the server to prepare your sandwich for you.

Ambiance: There‚Äôs a lot of space here to sit and it‚Äôs definitely a nice little place to chill after a long walk.

Would come back to try a different sandwich!</Text>

<userid>101367616453799645972< /userid><username>Ward Z</username><Date>1605815972905</Date>< rating>
4</rating>
< Review>
Au jus anyone? Philippe's  is a classic eatery with a nostalgic feel and a short  drive away to downtown LA. The female employees uniforms are a tastefully done and nice to look at; reminding me of a time when restaurant servers presented themselves with a touch of class! .Serving up a wide variety of soups, stews, breakfast and the ever famous sandwiches.We usually go for the au jus beef and it's tasty good! There's not much to it other than the bread of your choice, au jus dipping juice/sauce and a protein; in this case the beef and pastrami. The beef was good but the ratio of bread to beef was not balanced(same for the pastrami) too much bread or not enough protein.For the portion served ,it should have cost less; you do have the option to add mustard and or mayo. Next time I will have the sandwich dipped instead of dipping juice on the side. The sides were good but the brownie was dry and chalky. Outside is a large very nice clean tent set up for patio dinning; good thinking/planning on behalf of management and staff. So if your ever in the downtown area, be sure to visit Philippe the original.  Don't forget your masks!< /Review>

Colby Wakeman< /name>
<Review>We have been coming here for years! While it can be busy at times the food lines move quickly and there is almost always room to e sit and eat at the tables. Most people forget about the upstairs eating area. So if it looks packed on the main floor head up! When you get there find a line. While it may seem that some move faster then others they all move about the same speed. If you have some time walk around the inside of the building and check out the pictures on the walls of various Los Angeles history.

If you come for breakfast lunch or dinner you won‚Äôt be disappointed. There are enough options that everyone in your group will find something they like! Be sure to try the French dip. It‚Äôs what Philippe‚Äôs is known for. Just be cautious with the hot mustard on tables. You might want to try a little before you smother your sandwich with it!</Review></record></dataset><record>

<user_id>104611784406356148909</user_id><name>Monica Carrera< /name><Time>1508109266315</Time><Rate>5<//Rate>< text>
An L.A. institution. I can't visit downtown without coming here. Famous landmark for their famous French dipped sandwich.  Always a great sandwich, and sides. So many side dishes and desserts to choose from. The sandwiches whether beef or pork, are best double dipped and with their hot mustard. Although you can order just a dipped sandwich, if you want it a little drier. Yes, the mustard is "hot," so just add a little but to give your sandwich a kick. They have pickles, potato and macaroni salad, coleslaw, and potato chips. You can order a side salad, chili with or without beans, beef stew or a daily soup. They also offer many dessert options, such as fruit pies, cream pies, cakes, custard, tapioca or ice cream. They also offer breakfast early in the day. There are so many options to choose from, and they are all delicious.<//text>

< Review>
Delicious food that provides service quick! You will need to carry your tray of food after purchasing.

The line isn't the clearest but try to read the crowd.

The location is right at the corner, you won't miss it!

For those with allergies, be mindful of the sawdust.

Plenty of parking since they have two large lots nearby.

Seating is available further into the place itself and they also have a 2nd floor to accommodate guests.

Bathrooms are located in the back after the booths.</Review>

How don't I have a Philippe's review alrwady. My absolute favorite sandwich on earth! I love the beef dip, add Swiss, double dipped with a side of their delicious pickles.

Covid response is great. They have a huge tent with no walls in their parking lot. Friendly staff cleaning up after you and sanitizing each table. A full on sink with warm and cold water outside to wash up at, and of course sanitizer. The best response you can expect, and still the reliable tastiest sandwiches on the perfect bread.<//Text>

< review>
Enjoyed the experience of such an iconic location.   Tried a beef French dip and a pastrami, and got sides of potato salad, mac salad, and a pickled egg.  Food didn't quite meet our expectations; it wasn't bad but we didn't think it was quite the level of "famous" .   Glad that we followed another reviewers suggestion to request double-meat, double-dip.  Pricier but definitely a more impressive looking sandwich.  Disappointed that they forgot the requested cheese add-on but it wasn't a big deal since we weren't charged for it.  Service was friendly and prompt. Gotta try it at least once.  They do a good job with the current required safety measures and there's a nice outdoor dining area.</review>

$$-  Historic Delicatessen  sit down restaurant that's been serving french dip sandwiches since 1908 , clean , cozy atmosphere, friendly staff.
Sandwiches : Yummy & Tasty.
Serving the original french dipped sandwiches, and breakfast.
Breakfast  Served 6:00 a.m. to 10:30 a.m.
Options here counter service or take out.
Long lines but moves fast worth the wait.
My favorite here was the lamb dip sandwich, double dip.
Also very good  potato  salad, And by far one of the best tasting refreshing lemonade.
Very good size and tasty breakfast served here.
Also try their biscuits and gravy.
They have a wide range of dishes,  for french dip sandwiches,  such as beef dip, pork dip, turkey dip, ham dip, lamb dip, pastrami dip, ask for single dip, double dip, or wet.
They do tuna salad, cheese sandwich. And made to order peanut butter and jelly, Sandwich.
Stop on by grab a bite to eat,
With family, or friends, spread the word.

< Review>
This is a fun LA classic that any Angeleno needs to visit at least once. At more than 100 years old, Philippe‚Äôs still attracts crowds with its delicious sandwiches (my personal favorite is the pastrami). It is particularly popular before Dodger games and the lines can get pretty long but the staff is efficient at keeping things moving so don‚Äôt be discouraged if it looks busy.<//Review>

< time>
1517717745447< /time>
<Rate>5< /Rate>< text>
Highly recommended. Although I usually avoid blue cheese, I have a strict rule of accepting the advice of the people from whom I am buying food. When the lady suggested the crumbly oddity for my lamb dip, I hesitated for a brief moment before agreeing. As is usually the case in these situations, the employee was right. The blue cheese goes very well with the perfect lamb sitting atop the soggy roll. For those who enjoy drinks other than water with their food, the prices for hot tea, coffee, iced tea or lemonade are ridiculously cheap. Another important thing to mention is that they use quality paper napkins. More often than not, I find similar eateries using what amounts to tissue paper for napkins. I'm sure there are a few of you out there that can appreciate this fact about Philippe, as I do.</text>

< date>
1555220822823<//date>
<rating>4< /rating><Text>Classic for a reason. Got a double dipped beef dip sandwich with jack cheese. The french roll was firm enough to suck up the au jus, yet it still had a nice fluffy texture on the inside/light crisp on the outside. The beef itself was simply seasoned (which for me was a plus because roast beef sandwiches can easily lean on the salty side), and the temperature of the sandwich allowed for the cheese to not over-melt and get too gooey/messy. Overall, the simplicity of the sandwich lends to its deliciousness. It knows what it is, and is proud of it. The vibe of this place is kind of old school, yet in that endearing way. Kinda like if you‚Äôve been going there for years, and there is no expectation to be hip enough or fancy enough to eat there (lots of modern places give off this vibe). Overall, I definitely recommend to sandwich lovers/comfort food lovers!<//Text><userid>103965955659439129121< /userid><name>Luke Barbosa</name><Pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNVD55pkinYuWe0pQBteZTJSB2RNCfOApf6VVas=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /Pictures>< Gmap_id>

< Review>
I've been to both and like cheesesteaks in philly they both claim to be the first and the best.

The other one is both better and....at least feels older.
Phillippes' is great if you're at Union Station and missed your train so dart over to get something more than a pretzel, but any other time I wouldn't go there - they're meh at best.

If you ever have the chance to go inside too it's basically a tourist attraction and didn't keep any old LA charm it might've had when it began.</Review>

< review>
NOSTALGIC! That's what comes to mind when I come to this place. This place is an L.A. landmark. The dipped sandwiches are their staple. I get the lamb sandwich, double dipped, with a side of pickled beets and pickled hard boiled eggs. But they have many other options, not to mention their homemade desserts. I never regret stopping by. If I'm within a 30 mile radius I'll drive to it. Going to the Dodger game? Make it a tradition, and stop here to grab a bite. The place is buzzing with excitement. Staff is friendly and upbeat, not to mention the cute hostesses. But this place takes you back to a better place. Parking  is great, and nice views of the Los Angeles area. This is a must for anyone visiting us from out of town. Make yourself a favor, and stop by. Pics below to make your mouth water. Enjoy when you go.</review>

< review>
Our dear friend introduced us to this gem and we couldn't be happier. Went twice in the past month. First of all, it's BYOB with no corkage fee. You bring your own wine, beer, and liquor - as many as you want. The food is fantastic and the service is even better. The lady server (sorry, I forgot her name!)- is the sweetest EVER.

We've tried almost every dish and it tastes genuinely home made. My personal favorite was the lentil soup. SO GOOD.

Also, I left my wallet there last night & they kept it in a safe! SO SWEET. They truly care about their customers.

Love this place and recommend it to everyone!!</review>

< review>
Amazing place!

It has a very classic atmosphere to it. You walk up to the counter to place your order, you seat yourself anywhere that's available, and the line often stretches through the dining area sometimes out all the way to the sidewalk! The sandwiches are contenders for the "best sandwich ever" award. It's a French Dip because you can order a side of the sauce that is created in the sandwich making process. Their presentation is so unique - it's no wonder they've been around for over a 100 years!

‚Ä¢ HIGHLY RECOMMEND ‚Ä¢
If you are ever in the Los Angeles area and want a damn good sandwich, treat yourself right with a trip to an iconic sandwich<//review>

<user_id>104926909784286171501< /user_id><gmapID>0x80c2c65b315cd377:0xa05d997b42357a5< /gmapID>< Review>
What's not to love, this place is an institution - has been around forever, along with a lot of long-time staff, so you always see a familiar face to order from =).

Pro-tips:

If you are entering from the parking lot side and come down the stairs, don't feel the need to line up right there --  there are multiple lines, one in front of each cashier along the counter, so feel free to spread out!

Beef with American cheese is the best sandwich imho, and ask for extra jus for dunking üòÑ

If you've never had the spicy mustard, be careful, a little goes a loooong way (but do try it, it's delicious, and you can even buy a bottle of it to take home)

There is plenty of seating around the corner from the food counter, so you don't have to worry about finding a seat right in the immediate counter area<//Review>

I paid around $12 for a cold, small pastrami sandwich with way too much horseradish sauce on it that it upset my stomach.

The bread wasn't that great either and the dipping sauce was a kind of disgusting cold salad dressing.

If I had it to do over again I would go to Arby's (a better French Dip) or Subway (better value and footlong).

My first experience, just gross. Possibly overated. The employees are very friendly though.</text>< Pictures>

< Review>
still awesome after all these years. French dip sandwich, pickle egg, chilli, pie, everything is good. I personally love the lamp one with Swiss cheese and always get it triple dip, but it can get a little too soggy, so for those who don't like it like that, double dip should be your limit. and don't forget to add a little of their own mustard. it has a real kick to it in a good way, like wasabi. they're still open for take out during the pandemic and they also have an outdoor area for those who really want to sit down and eat.</Review>

<Date>1504837375734<//Date><text>I don't know who Philippe is but he sure knows how to wet his beef<//text><user_id>106171572282355311439< /user_id><GmapID>0x80c2c65b315cd377:0xa05d997b42357a5</GmapID><pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPFGPyqurQ3j_IqPXowLHaM6nCmgJB-GKdMHszQ=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//pics><resp>None</resp>< user_name>

<Date>1564646279944<//Date>< rating>
5<//rating>
< name>
James Wesley< /name>
<resp>None<//resp>< review>
This place has been a bucket list stop for me, for quite sometime. I finally had the chance today to visit Philippe's, as I am a self proclaimed connoisseur of beef dip sandwiches.

Our visit began bright and early on a Saturday morning, we just happened to be in town for an event. As we entered, we were greeted with the nostalgic feeling of old Los Angeles, and the aroma of roasted meat.. Mmmmm. The menu was pretty basic for lunch, mostly dipped sandwiches, with all types of meats. There was a vast array of other tasty treats including puddings, pastries and salads in the refrigerator box under the counter.

We got down to business right away, because the lines were minimal, which isn't the norm according to regulars. We decided to share a meal, so that we would have room to eat at another local favorite later.. lol. On the menu for us was the "double dipped" roast beef sandwich, dill pickles and a side of macaroni salad, and a couple of frosty IPA's on tap. We really wanted to order one of everything, but as I said, we needed room for another place near by. The sandwich was served split for us, and presented nicely with the kosher dill pickles. The macaroni salad was served as a generous helping in a side dish. The roast beef was tender, the French roll delicious, and the macaroni salad on point. And OMG the pickles ! We basically inhaled our food, it was soo delicious !

All and all, this was a great experience that will be repeated again in the future. My only advice would be to sit somewhere other than where the line forms. I felt the people basically breathing down my neck, as they salivated over my food. And every other patron must have been sick, as there was a lot of damn coughing going on way too close for comfort.<//review>

An ICON, and a MUST-STOP.

Classic, original French dip sandwich in downtown LA. Where celebrities and the downtrodden rub elbows at communal tables with business men and tourists.
They used to be cash only, but now they accept cards and that ups the convenience.

My ‚Äúgo to‚Äù is the double meat, single dip, with Swiss and lots of their signature horseradish.</review>

<userid>113041695347928939930<//userid><name>Mayra Hernandez< /name><time>1571523883688< /time><rating>5</rating>< review>
My husband has been here a few times mostly during lunchtime. Today he recommended this as our breakfast place. I ofcourse was very much looking forward to finally try the famous Philippe The Original. I took a few minutes to look over the menu before making my decision. My husband, he went with his favorite and usual, the beef dip "single dip". A  delicious and savory prime beef on a french roll dipped in their authentic "jus". I wanted a breakfast item, so went with the veggie Omelette. It was light and the veggies were perfectly cooked. I was pleasantly surprised that it had sliced cherry tomatoes. The Omelette came with potatoes and I chose white toast since we also ordered biscuits and gravy. The biscuits were pretty good. The gravy was also good, had minced sausage in it. Which ofcourse made it even more tasty. Overall I enjoyed our breakfast. The restaurant and food both did not disappoint. With so many selections, I'll be looking forward to our next time.</review>

<Date>1575894186191< /Date><user>107781854678613472810< /user>< review>
Came in for my first time. I was skeptical because I'm not a sandwich person.
We ordered a double dipped beef, and a double dipped NYC Pastrami. They were amazing. Honestly the best tasting sandwiches I've had.the flavors and texture were amazing. I can't wait to come back.
I loved the interior it's like a deli that's stuck in the past, they still have newspapers and phone booths, a cashier that sells candy and other things.
If your in the area...even if your not in the area check this place out, it's worth the drive.</review>

<user_name>Nicole Copley< /user_name>< time>
1562745830959<//time>
<Rate>5</Rate><text>As we entered, we were greeted with the nostalgic feeling of old Los Angeles, and the aroma of roasted meat.. Mmmmm. The menu was pretty basic for lunch, mostly dipped sandwiches, with all types of meats. There was a vast array of other tasty treats including puddings, pastries and salads in the refrigerator box under the counter.

On the menu for us was the "double dipped" roast beef sandwich, dill pickles and a side of macaroni salad, and a couple of frosty IPA's on tap. We really wanted to order one of everything, but as I said, we needed room for another place near by. The sandwich was served split for us, and presented nicely with the kosher dill pickles. The macaroni salad was served as a generous helping in a side dish. The roast beef was tender, the French roll delicious, and the macaroni salad on point. And OMG the pickles ! We basically inhaled our food, it was soo delicious !

All and all, this was a great experience that will be repeated again in the future.</text>< pics>

<GmapID>0x80c2c65b315cd377:0xa05d997b42357a5< /GmapID><rate>5</rate><review>While it's up for debate on who originated the first french dip, opening in 1908, Philippe's is definitely one of the first places offering french dipped sandwiches in Los Angeles. You line up, order from the counter and on of the servers hand makes and dips your sandwich, slices your pie and fills your coffee. There's a variety of meats, cheeses, and the option for a double dip if you want your sandwich extra wet.

They also have have a great breakfast if you get there early enough, a wide selection of pies, salads, and drinks. It is almost always extremely crowded, although during off hours you can sometimes walk right up and order.<//review>< response>

<userid>107168861364054077381<//userid><name>Dominic Irizarry</name><Date>1579992324739< /Date><Rating>5< /Rating>< text>
A historical institution, Philippe's has been making french dipped sandwiches since 1908. The roast beef deep is my favorite, and getting it "wet" has the French roll cut in half before being dipped in the juice from the roast beef. The house horseradish mustard packs a punch, and is available to take home on the way out (and in local grocers)<//text>

< Review>
I first saw this place on Food Network's "Diners Drive-ins and Dives" many, many years ago. As soon as I finished the episode I would come here one day and slay the hot pastrami sandwich! Many years later I moved from the upper Midwest to the sunny sunny state of CA, near the bay area, no where near this restaurant. By happen chance my parents moved to the SD area and so while driving down to visit them found the perfect excuse to stop in at this establishment. Needless to say, the sandwich did not disappoint. I am pretty sure that I inhaled the sandwich so fast I'm not even certain if I tasted any of it...regardless, it was very enjoyable and I would definitely make a trip back when I am in the area.</Review>

< text>
Like Cielito Lindo around the corner, this is another LA institution, dating back to 1908. But I'm not from LA, I haven't been eating here since I was a kid, and I don't have the rose tint of nostalgia. The signature sandwich - well, It's a good beef sandwich - much improved by adding the mustard. You're eating history as much as you're eating a sandwich.< /text>

< Text>
been going there over 50 years , looks the same but of course things do change as well. $8.99 for the beef sandwich I remember $2.00, all the older faces behind the counter are all young faces now, the hot mustard no longer in the ceramic holder but a plastic squeeze bottle , I think I go there now for the memories more than the food, when it's was my mom and dad and two younger brothers, when we were a family</Text>

< text>
A Los Angeles classic. I've been going my whole life, and it never disappoints. All of the food I've had there is good. I tried the pastrami sandwich for the first time on my last visit and it was stellar. I recommend ordering a "Beef Double Dip" if you can't decide. Add some cheese and apply their in-house mustard yourself for a unique taste. The lines look long but they move pretty quick. It's a neat place were all walks of life come together.</text>

< user_id>
115901258481024558765< /user_id>
<rate>5< /rate><user_name>robin sneed< /user_name><date>1573581216413< /date>< text>
A restaurant that has been around for over a hundred years! And, it's still packed every day, up the stairs and out the door. There's only one Philippe in the world and you can now have these delicious sandwiches shipped. The place where French Dips were invented by a police officer and a sandwich maker. A place where a glass of iced tea is cents (sense) and not dollars. Near the historic Olvera Street which boasts fresh pan dulce and the oldest adobes in the nation. Also near China Town. Make Philippe a visit on an historic day in downtown LA and you won't be sorry!<//text>

<user_id>111734271779192816486<//user_id>< Resp>

< Review>
This tiny little restaurant in a strip mall is easy to miss but I've had consistently excellent food there on repeated occasions.
It's clean, quiet, family run and with excellent and very friendly service.
The food tastes incredibly fresh and is not swimming in sauce like in other Chinese restaurants.
We really enjoyed the following on repeat visits: wonton soup, orange chicken, salt & pepper calamari, crispy green beans, oyster mushrooms with baby bok choi.
This has become our family go to Chinese restaurant whenever we're in the area.</Review>

< Text>
Love the French dipped sandwiches. I always get the beef with coleslaw, lemonade and a pickle! The ice cream is soft and delicious. I ate it the desert before the meal and it was perfect.
It gets crowded sometimes, but there is plenty of seating. The lower floor is more homey and welcoming with the floor and wall decor. The top is a stark contrast.
Add a bit of the brown sauce from the squeeze bottles if you want a bit of a spicy kick to the sandwiches.</Text>

<UserId.>102143509529737289762< /UserId.><date>1573340591549< /date>< GmapID>

< user_name>
Marie</user_name>
< review>
Philippe's is so delicious it'll make you forget how pricey it can be. The food is comforting and always consistent when you come back. Philippe's has two parking lots to accomodate, and plenty of service lines. There is much to be said for a simply made meal to be delicious, memorable, and worth it.
This is a restaurant that used to be great, and is still great currently. If lines are a bother, I suggest visiting late at night or right after they open. And having a coffee is tradition.
This is a place for the locals, as some menu items (french-dipped sandwiches), may not seem like much unless you know which extras and changes to ask for, which is not apparent to new visitors. When in doubt, add the horseradish mustard to enjoy the magic that the rest of the Angeleno's are raving about.<//review>

<rate>5</rate>< review>
Try the beef stew; beef and vegetables in their natural juices - and it's $4.  Try anything else and you'll love it all.  Counter ordering (about 10 stations), they slice the meat you order for the famous dipped sandwiches right off the bone, dish out your sides, and handle your payment.  Don't miss this.

I just had a spinach mushroom onion omelet.  $9.75. with it came a half a plate of perfectly crusted hash brown potatoes, two large pieces of toast with butter and jam, a side of salsa, and a cup of coffee, amazing.<//review>

<rating>5<//rating>< Review>
This is definitely worth a stop for one of the original French-dipped sandwiches.  It's a decent sized sandwich costs about $8.50, and the flavor is great.  It's kinda comparable to a dipped Italian beef sandwich that you'd find at a Portillo's in Chicago, but this one uses bread with a harder crust which keeps the au jus from leaking out as you eat the sandwich.  Cool vintage atmosphere in the restaurant too.<//Review>

Robert Ford<//username>
<time>1549292525115<//time><Rating>5< /Rating>< Text>
A must place to stop. I have been going here since the late 60s. Whenever we were anywhere near Los Angeles we would stop there for a meal. My grandparents would drive in from Orange County. They had been going there since before they moved there when the 101 freeway was built. Dont let the rustic appearance scare you away. There is always a fast moving line up of people waiting for a delicious sandwich.  It could be locals, construction workers, or people stopping by after an evening at the theater. The food is delicious no matter what time of day. Don't miss out on this little slice of local LA pie. These are the best sandwiches I have ever had.< /Text>

An "Icon" of sandwiches in the L.A. area. There are places you don't miss when you visit certain cities, Philippes is one of those places. So if you're in the L.A. area, on business or vacation, make sure you stop by Philippes and have a French Dip, you won't be sorry, that is unless you miss it, then it'll be a crying shame!< /Review>< Pics>

100469778403209129538< /userid>
< user_name>
Mark Thistlewaite</user_name>
< Date>
1541399923761<//Date>
<Rate>5<//Rate>< review>
Ancient place in the middle of downtown LA, where the menu items have changed little over the years. The star of the menu is the double dip French dip, on a homemade French roll. Be sure and get a side of either potato salad or macaroni salad. And don't forget dessert, their pies are wonderful.

As you sit on the saw dust covered dining room, try the hot mustard. If you had a cold before you came in, if you overuse the mustard on the squeeze bottle, you won't have a cold leaving.

The coffee is cheap and good, so is the beef stew. They also offer a hearty breakfast.< /review>

< Review>
Clean restaurant. Order at the counter and bring to one of the many tables available. If you want pancakes, get there before last call for breakfast-I think around 10:30AM. Had the single dip turkey on rye. Loaded it up with the signature mustard; it was the bomb!! Coleslaw kicked and pickles hit the spot too. Grab a beer and wash it down! If your nose is a bit stuffed up, just add more mustard to your sandwich and you‚Äôll be able to breathe and smell anything from a mile away. The Original-nuff said.</Review>

< text>
This place is an L.A classic and should be declared a historic landmark!  It's been around since 1908!!  The french dipped sandwiches are what they are best known for.  Personally I like the lamb, but all the meats are lean and good quality and they don't skimp.  You can also order with extra meat if you are REALLY hungry.

Whenever I'm in the area, I gotta get my Phillipe on!<//text>

<Text>They have best French dip sandwich. The lines can be a little long and slow. So if you're in a hurry this is not the place for a quick meal. Also seems like their prices seemed to keep going up and up every time I go. It can get pricey if you add any side or drinks. Spent almost $13 for a sandwich,side of mac and can of coke. This is an icon, and any resident of LA has to familiarize themselves with sawdust on the floor, hot mustard, and meat juice all over their fingers. <name>Train Your Zombie<//name><time>1571521128183< /time><rate>5< /rate>< review>
Legendary LA staple! My gf brought me by in the morning, and I just loved it üëåüëÄ‚ù§Ô∏è. It‚Äôs spitting distance from the LA Amtrak Union Station, so great spot to eat if you are traveling or coming in town from somewhere.

There was a short line, very friendly staff, huuuuge space w several rooms and all kinds of historical local memorabilia on the walls. It was a lot of fun to see. Loved the row of telephone booths, and the openness of it, early in the morning it is full of ppl on their way to work. Seemed a lot of locals love having breakfast here before work, rather than home.

Still sawdust on the ground. Not my style, had to ask what that was, looked weird to me, on cement floor, but am foreign, so not culturally relevant to me, and it does seem that everyone else loved it.

The food was fast, nice size portions, and very tasty. Gulped it down in 5 min.

People here are friendly. Many seem regulars, and very interactive. Others more reserved, but overall a friendly vibe.<//review>

< Text>
Transport yourself back to 1910 in Los Angeles with this cafeteria style style French dip sandwich.  The pork is the sweetest and fattiest, the beef is just succulent and the lamb is savory.  A little potato salad and a lemonade with a piece of pie and everyone is happy. Truly delicious after all these years.</Text>

<Text>Truly deserving of its status. The French dip is as good as advertised, and the atmosphere is so dope. Quick, bustling, and efficient, yet never feeling cold or rushed. Two stories with plenty of places to sit and grub (plus the feel of hallways and different rooms is an oddly nice touch). Sandwiches are excellent, sides are bomb, desserts are delicious, even the lemonade is above average. Only complaint is parking but I mean come on, it's L.A.</Text></record>

<Text>Philippe The Original is a part of my pre-game ritual whenever I'm on my way to Dodger Stadium. My usual order is the roast beef (double dipped) with a pickle and macaroni salad with a lemonade. You can't go wrong with the potato salad or coleslaw either ... great old-fashioned deli fare with a historic vibe! It's especially fun when 3/4 of the crowd is decked out in their Dodger gear! If you're there early for a day game, the breakfasts are as dandy as Sandy! Really, if you love tradition, the Dodgers or just great old time L.A. eateries, Philippe The Original is the boss of them all!!!< /Text>< Pics>

<Name>Michael Kamali<//Name><Date>1563921376399</Date>< Rating>

<review>It took a long time to make it through the line to the counter of Phillipe The Orginal French Dip sandwich. It was well worth the wait..

The decor is sparse, old model trains, pictures of long forgotten people, decades old news paper articles, and hooks on the wall to hang your coat and hat.. Thw seating is open family style, there is always a space for everyone and if you want some privacy make a trip upstairs or a both on the ground floor. Fresh sawdust is thrown on the floors every morning to give that old time flash back salon feel...

Phillipe is a 111 years and still going strong from the first day it opened its doors.

Grab a fine glass of wine or a craft beer and taste the flavor that put them in the map..<//review><Pics>None</Pics>< Response>

<user>102943114490430648614< /user><name>Ross Berteig<//name>< Date>
1492988991429</Date>
<Rating>5</Rating><review>A Los Angeles classic dive with great history and even greater sandwiches, Philippe's has been an occasional stop for me since I moved to Southern California in the early 1980s. In all that time, it has changed remarkably little, and judging from the photos on the wall, it hasn't changed all that much since its founding.

I almost always have the lamb dip, they slice the meat right off a bone. But they are best known for the beef dip, being one of several restaurants with a plausible story and claim to being its originator. But don't neglect their sides, they do a decent egg custard, pickled eggs, pies, salads, and more.<//review><pics>None</pics>< Resp>

Delicious, mouthwatering french dripped sandwiches in a casual settings. Be prepared to wait in line for a while during busy periods, but trust me it is worth the wait. If the sandwich doesn't fill you, they have an excellent range of desserts to choose from!

Service is fast, staff are friendly and helpful regarding the menu. We were not sure whether we wanted our sandwiches dipped so the lady behind the counter put some in a small pot for us to try. She insisted it was good and she was not wrong.<//review>

<Rate>5< /Rate><review>Love the quaint cafeteria style, casual atmosphere of Philippe the Original. Order at the deli counter, fairly inexpensive but delicious sandwiches(beef, lamb turkey, ham, pastrami...double dipped, add hot mustard.!) various sides(chili, potato/macaroni salad, coleslaw soups, pickled eggs, etc.), desserts(pie, cake, custard, tapioca, baked apples, etc.), not to mention the candy counter and craft beer(and extensive wine list), and sit at communal tables surrounded by historic pictures of Los Angeles. < Review>
Didn't think I would enjoy this place as much as I did. The Beef Dip and the pastrami are both really good. Not a fancy sandwich, just very simple and flavorful. The restaurant itself is an old, dumpy cafeteria with sawdust on the floor, but the sandwiches are worth going back for. Lines can pile up fast but seem to move quickly.<//Review>

< text>
We went yesterday, and it wasn't too crowded. My wife and I got two beef dips, a chocolate cake, a lemonade (only 90 cents,) and we brought in Won Kock Chinese food for our daughter and cousin. Beef dips were excellent, and I'm already craving another one. They have a lot of space to handle all the people in there, and a lot of great train stuff and pictures to look at on the walls. If you are in the area, you have to try this place out at least once.< /text>

< Review>
The very best Beef Dips in Southern California. An excellent choice of sandwiches, side dishes and desserts. A cup of coffee is only $0.45, which is delightful and has a fresh ground taste.

Whenever I am in downtown Los Angeles visiting and eating at Phillipes is a must. Philippe's recently celebrated their 110th year anniversary. There is a reason this restaurant has been in existence for 110 years. Quality is foremost and prices are very reasonable.

This is a Los Angeles landmark. The food is monumental.< /Review>

<user>115225314587868778168<//user>< name>
Crystal Yang< /name>
< time>
1551975903543</time>
< Rate>
5</Rate>
< Review>
Almost always busy with long lines, and a bit pricey, but excellent dipped sandwiches. I usually get either the beef or lamb sandwich. The double dip is perfect for any sandwich, just cuz the single dipped is a bit too dry for my taste. Don't be fooled by the color, the pickled eggs are the BEST and is a must-try item there.

As for parking, the one by the shop itself is small and always full. Alternatives are street parking, or the bigger parking lot across the street. It might be more of a walk, so it may not be suitable for disabled/handicapped people if the handicapped parking is already full. That is up to the individual for judgment.</Review>

< text>
Yes indeed it's the original place for the French dip sandwich. For those that haven't, stop by when you hit Union station, or swing through Chinatown as it's really close.

Go ahead and spoil yourself and grab one with double meat. You absolutely won't regret it. The place is like a weird little time capsule, saw dust on the floors, long wooden benches, pickled eggs and everything!

Also, keep your eyes peeled when you visit, you'll see plenty of Hollywood figures pop in and out.<//text>

<Text>Wow, i don't know where to start...
My girls and I were so excited to try this place after seeing it on Man vs. Food but unfortunately our experience was not even close to what we expected. First of all the sign says nothing about breakfast not being served after 10:30 am on the menu. We were about 4th in line and arrived at 10:35....two separate customers in front of us ordered breakfast and when it was our turn the lady at the counter said breakfast was over at 10:30.  I explained that we got in line past 10:30 and other customers ordered breakfast and got it, so she said I will do it this time only. I didn't feel it was right for her to be acting like she was doing me a favor, when she was letting other customers order breakfast past the time they were serving it. Then, she comes back out and said we don't have enough bacon for both of your breakfasts so we'll give you sausage. After we received our order we noticed other people were getting bacon. Wasn't very impressed with the beef dip sandwich that I ordered, it wasn't bad but in my opinion didn't meet the rave reviews that others give. To top it off my daughter had egg shells in her fried eggs. I'm glad others enjoy it but we will never go back....so disappointed</Text>< user_name>

< Review>
While the food is good and the building historic, its popularity has lead to it being crowded all the damn time!!! When I'm feeling in the mood for Philippe's I will swing by and get a sandwhich here. The lamb sandwich is really good. Their pies are also good. The food is a bit pricey though

If you want to come here you best be prepared to spend a LONG time in line. Don't even think about coming here during a Dodgers game because the lines are out the door.

In conclusion while I do like the food here I don't feel like waiting forever for it</Review>

< Review>
It's a classic for a reason. The roast beef is of course the signature item and it doesn't disappoint. I do like to add the mustard that can be found at the communal tables throughout the place. Beet purple pickled egg and I am a happy camper. On the down side the mac salad was ok, not great. Oh, don't be weirded out when ordering. You put the money on the tray and the ladies bring it to the one cashier, then they bring your change back to you at the display cases where you ordered. Give 'em a nice tip, they are working hard!< /Review>

Love this place. First time I ate here was after my son's "urban hike" (10 mile hike around the city) with his Boy Scout troop. They've got delicious dips (beef dip, double dipped beef, etc.). Always fun and delicious. Go back in time 100 years (though its first site was replaced by a freeway). This site can be glimpsed in a Charlie Chaplin film called "Police," I believe. <rating>5</rating>< Review>
This is old Los Angeles. The food is excellent. (My favorite is the lamb dip sandwich!) You order at the counter and your food is prepared, by hand, right then and there. There are booths, but try the communal tables. This is a great place to have a meal before or after a Dodger game.</Review>

<Gmap_id>0x80c2c65b315cd377:0xa05d997b42357a5<//Gmap_id>< text>
Old staple restaurant in heart of original downtown right next to Olivera St Mission and Union Station. Everything is Al le cart but reasonably priced. Parking free and good, except at lunch time during the work week as this is a favorite spot for police, fire and most all city, county, state and federal workers. Then there are the dodger fan regulars who are there for meals before a game. Vegetarian meals not their thing, but they do have good salads.</text>

< Text>
One of the oldest restaurants in Los Angeles & claims to have introduced the French dip sandwich. Place is very reasonably priced & it is about MEAT. You stand in line -it's always crowded. You order & your food is put on a tray. You carry to your table in the large multi room dining area. Great sides & beer. Be sure to take home some hot mustard.<//Text>

<review>Quite a few reviews for this place, so I'll make it short.  CASH ONLY.

To Order: Proceed to any available carver along the counter; if there are lines, individual lines form for each carver.

< username>

< Date>
1500921063637< /Date>
<Rate>5<//Rate>< Review>
Delicious french dip sandwiches in a century-old location just blocks from the historic and picturesque Union Station and Olvera Street. There are lots of comfort foods from a great potato salad to pickled eggs. Sawdust on the floor, a little gum and candy counter, and nostalgic uniforms of the counter staff will transport you back to a different era the second you step inside. Lines move quickly, lemonade and ice tea are inexpensive, and the hot mustard will clear your sinuses, guaranteed.< /Review>

5<//rating>
< review>
Visited here while waiting to change Amtrak trains at Union Station. Easy 10 minute walk from the station and quick take-out service got us back in plenty of time to eat before getting on our train. It was 6:30 a.m., but I couldn't pass up the French Dipped. It was great! The beef was tender and the bread fresh (and just the right soggy). Also got an order of biscuits and gravy and some pancakes. Both were fresh and tasted terrific! I would recommend Philippe's to anyone looking for a quick meal from a local establishment.</review>

108107724841669105360</userid>
<username>Tom Llewellyn<//username>< date>
1490213055848< /date>
< Rate>
5<//Rate>
<review>We come here for two things: the food and restaurant.

As the creator of the French dip, Philippe's delivers consistently quality food. But they offer so much more than just good sandwiches, their sides (especially the potato and macaroni salads) and pies are delicious also!

From the sawdust on the floor and model train museum in the back room to the old school phone booths and candy counter, Philippe's offers plenty of charm.

Private booths and public cafeteria style seating are both available. I prefer to pull up a seat at one of the long tables and make new friends.

Don't forget to slather a bit of Philippe's famous hot mustard (in bottles on each table and for sale at the candy counter) on your sandwich for the full experience.<//review>< pics>
None<//pics>

< text>
Philippe french dip sandwiches are in LA staple and continue to draw me in, no matter what the hour is. I almost have an emotional experience with the place; anytime that I returned from a night of drinking, my pals and I would always grab a bite to eat from the establishment. Although their breakfast is not on par with other Great LA eateries such as The Pantry, Philippe holds up with its own unique experience. Nothing tops a lunch like a French dip sandwich and coleslaw. Their drinks are refreshing, cheap, and in perfect portions. The staff is always friendly, and moves quickly. I could say that one thing that is required upon every visit to the restaurant is their house mustard sauce that that sits upon every table. Philippe is a must-try.< /text>

<gmap_id>0x80c2c65b315cd377:0xa05d997b42357a5</gmap_id><username>Jerri Talley<//username><Time>1516173077254< /Time><UserId.>106043816300561069052</UserId.>< rate>
4<//rate>
<text>It almost lives up to its hype. The sandwiches are good but not amazing, it definitely isn't worth traveling out of the way or fighting traffic if you're not familiar with the area. However if you're nearby or really want to travel downtown to try it then you probably won't be disappointed. Counter serve, it's a bit unorganized for those not familiar with the style of service. If you like your French dip juicy then definitely get it wet because double dip isn't enough. I tried the straight chili that has no beans and it was good but a tad bland, imo. The baked apple was also good and a unique menu item that I don't see around too often. Lots of side item choices and other menu items for breakfast if french dip isn't what you're looking for.</text><Pictures>None<//Pictures><response>None< /response></record></dataset><record>

115925722897795932732< /user_id>
< name>
Benjamin Yang<//name>
< time>
1541865405115</time>
<rate>3< /rate>< Text>
It was a nice leisurely walk from the city hall if you like me are a tourist adament about no renting a car. The place is not difficult to find and is also a short walk from the union station. The resturant is popular and the counter service was prompt and friendly.

We had the dipped beef and the serving size and taste was on point. I like how there was the sogginess goodness of the sauce as well as a light crunch from the outer skin of the French roll. And yes additional mustard on the beef does make a positive difference in taste. The soup was a little underwhelming though, and I had the Manhatten chowder bowl.

Whilst there is generally favourable reviews and I personally liked the food, I would not travel all the way out to get a taste. But it is a wonderful side trip from the city hall. On a side note, did I see the chef from 2 broke girls there? ...<//Text>

<username>Eric Fregoso</username>< Review>
Went here for lunch with my band mates and I thought this restaurant would be good considering it was featured by Zagat and had many positive reviews. Ordered a lamb sandwich with Swiss  cheese (extra charge) and a slice of chocolate cake, total around $16. The atmosphere screamed hype. The main room was very crowded and there were weird wood shavings on the floor that I almost slipped on numerous time. Since the main room was crowded we went upstairs. The rooms looked like I was eating in a woman's prison workhouse mess hall like in Iron Jawed Angels.  The food itself was not like I expected. It was very plain and utterly simple. I don't think this was worth the price. The signature "French Dip" was also quite plain to me. The cake was okay, nothing special. Overall eh food, nothing special.</Review>

<text>Parking is free in the parking lots for Philippe's customers. In L.A. That's amazing, people. Food is always good; service is top notch -- all of the employees I've ever come in contact with have been there a very long time and have great attitudes. There's a lot on the menu, but the dips are where it's at for me. Single dip is dipped on one side of the bread only; double dip is both sides; and wet is soaked. I enjoy the double -- it's wet enough to taste it, but doesn't fall apart on you. Sometimes wet is called for and the fork sees some action, but most often the double is home. Great place, great history, great people, great food.< /text>< Time>

< Text>
I've been coming since I'm a kid when my father would bring us. The entire area is a place out of time so walking the area as a tourist, not much has changed in 50 years.

I noticed they updated the menu board, the old one must have been there at least 50 years, so I don't see why it needed to go. Maybe millennials couldn't read the simple font. Haha. Hey, I just realized I didn't see the pickled eggs on the counter. Hmm.

The food hasn't changed and most of the interior hasn't. It still is a meal back in time. The amount they serve seems small but that's what it was. The food isn't OMG, but it is good. Most important it is fresh. The iced tea is real tea, not the stuff from a powder they pass off as tea at most places, even the fast casual places.  Same for the lemonade. The beef is fresh sliced roast beef, not fresh pressed into a round shape, add fillers and preservatives roast beef. If all you know is Arby's, you don't know good.

Go eat, bring cash. The only thing they did as a concession to the passing of time is add an ATM in the corner by the stairs.

While you're eating see if you can spot the last original pane of glass that had managed to survive at least 100 years.<//Text>

My 93y/o father -who grew up  in L.A. went here-as all my brother and extended family. Great food,prices this old Los Angeles icon still has sawdust on the floor (to soak up the blood-+I mean food spills)a a row of payphones with folding doors,a free parking lot for patrons(non-existant in downtown anywhere!)great staff and patrons from every culture,walk of life. Buy the brown mustard and a coffee mug-it the mug is thick so the coffee stays hot longer and the brown mustard is classic. <rate>5</rate>< Review>
The sandwich might not look pretty but it's just so good.  Get it double dipped so it's not as dry and it'll create this wonder contrast between the crunchy exterior French roll and the melt in your aujuis part of the roll.  Put some of their house Russian mustard and it's heavenly.  It is truly a LA institution and it still has that old tyme vibe that's missing in most part of LA.< /Review>

< user_name>
Laura Rosas</user_name>
< userid>
100297970703120176422<//userid>
< Rating>
2<//Rating>
< Text>
This place looks like a mix of my high school cafeteria and a bar. So, very historic and just like a bar it was poorly lit. It was very clean and the service was pretty fast for it being a Sunday morning. Servers and busser were all very polite.

The french dip sandwiches weren't all they're made out to be though. If you're into small bland soggy sandwiches with a few slices of meat that's lightly seasoned with maybe onion powder and black pepper.. This is definitely the spot for you.
Also the sauce that they put out on the table is not the way to go. Tasted like they mixed wasabi and mustard.
Enjoyed the experience made me reminisce but never coming back.< /Text>

<Review>I have lived in L.A. for 30 years and counting.  Yet, the first time I tried Phillipe's was April of this year.  Let me tell you, I had been missing out!!  The lines can be long and the service a little slow but it doesn't matter when you finally get your food.  The French Dip is the way to go.  Sinlge. With au jus on the side.  The more I come here the more I love the place.  Their lemonade is great too.  I had their custard pie which was great.  I would totally get the filling from here and the pie crust from House of Pies to make the perfect custard pie.  I highly recommend this place if you love beef sandwiches.  Parking is great as they have two lots. Pricey but worth it.< /Review>< Rating>
5</Rating>

<user_name>Paul Peterson</user_name><Time>1500102520517</Time>< Pics>

< review>
It's like stepping back in time at this historical downtown LA eatery.  The selection of dishes, sandwiches, desserts, and drinks is awesome!  Breakfast, Lunch, or Dinner, it doesn't matter, all the dishes are wonderful and a great reminder of how great food is supposed to taste.  Service is fast and friendly.  The price is excellent and the atmosphere is like stepping back in time (in a good way).  Everytime I'm in downtown or shopping at Olvera Street, I stop in for bite to eat. Parking is okay and peek lunch and dinner hours can make you wait, but don't get upset, the food is worth it.  Definitely a must do if you go to LA.</review>

I've been to Philippe's multiple times.  When you go to a restaurant that is world renowned for French Dip, you should get the French Dip.  Which I have had many times before.  And it's super yummy.

Philippe's is a great, fun, historical restaurant, located in the Chinatown area of Los Angeles.  They offer a wide selection of foods, breakfast, lunch and dinner.  They are famous for their French Dips.  Ask for a double dip (bread dipped in au jus), with your choice of beef, pork, turkey, lamb.  Their coleslaw was good!  I loved their potato salad last visit.  And their desserts look scrumptious!

There is free parking in the lot behind and across the street on Ord Street.. but don't go window shopping around the area as they will tow your car!  Parking is for customers only and strictly enforced!

They have a variety of seating.  Family style (share a table with some locals.. you'd be surprised all the history you can learn), table seating and booths.  Do yourself a favor and take the extra time to walk upstairs and in the front and check out the unique rooms, history and souvenirs.

There's saw dust on the floors.  You need to wait in lines to  order, but they go fast!  But do know what you want and remember.. it's CASH ONLY!!!

Also.. this is a great place to stop before the Dodger game, pick up a few dips and chips and head off to the game.  :)< /review>

<user>104694039954780464427<//user><name>Jerald Bahena< /name><Time>1435737171233< /Time>< review>
The success and longevity of a restaurants life is hard to predict. That being said, I say with 100% conviction that Phillippe's the Original will be around for a long time.

Phillippes has character. The ambiance is timeless. The textures and tones of the materials and lighting are very soft on the eyes.

The food is wonderful. Sandwiches are delicious. Prices are low. I would recommend Tapioca. Lemonade is 75 cents.

While every bite shouldn't include hot mustard, it nicely  compliments the sandwich.</review>

103638109282673764332</UserId.>
< user_name>
Owen</user_name>
<Time>1514580044193</Time><Rate>4<//Rate>< Review>
No more legacy prices but the food tastes great. If they ask if you want gravy on your biscuits and you say yes, you will get gravy on three biscuits and charge you 5 bucks for them. Don't know why they can't just put gravy on the biscuits on the breakfast plates. It came in a little terrine dish and was like a thick chowder, which was actually the soup of the day. It's not cheap. A pastrami sandwich will set you back almost 10 bucks with tax included. And the coffee cups are small so you are basically paying for the same $2 coffee but for half the cup.</Review>
