< user_id>
107004408055073353040</user_id>
< Text>
I've been going here since I was a kid and hopefully will continue to until I'm an old man. If you haven't been before, you have to try the beef dip. If you're looking to branch out, my favorite sandwich is a lamb with blue cheese, double dipped, with plenty of mustard. Sometimes, if I'm really hungry, I'll go for the potato salad and some custard. I don't know if they still allow it, but a great way to beat the prices at dodger stadium is to get a couple of sandwiches to go and take them to the game with you.

The lines can be a little intimidating to first timers, but don't fret. Take a second to scope out the lines and you can usually find a short one hidden at the end, or with two cashiers instead of one.< /Text>

< time>
1417652430798< /time>
< review>
Very neat place... a touch of another era.  I'd go more for the nostalgia than the food though.  The building shows its age (in a good way) and it seems like they haven't changed a whole lot in their extensive and successful history.

I had the beef french dip.  The portion was on the small side and the au jus was a little salty.  I'd say that is was OK.  However, the blueberry pie was amazing.  All of the prices are from another era as well, with lemonade for $0.75 and iced tea for $0.65.  For a drink, sandwich, and pie, everything was $15.  The staff was very nice and the food was prepared quickly.

Overall, I'd recommend checking it out.< /review>

Peter Manderino< /username>

5<//rate>
< review>
Extremely busy but worth the wait. Fantastic classic sandwich from the oldest locally owned restaurant in LA. I had the beef double dipped minus the cheese. The beef was tender with no gristle or much fat. The aus jus was perfectly seasoned. Wasn't salty at all which most places use salt instead of the natural flavors from the meat. If you like a little kick, try the mustard. It has great flavor and heat from the horse radish. If I ever make it back to Los Angeles, I will be returning.< /review>

<gmap_id>0x80c2c65b315cd377:0xa05d997b42357a5<//gmap_id>< Text>
I was so disappointed, I haven't eaten at Philippe's in quite a while, and decided to go with a friend. I always get the lamb sandwich, double dipped. Usually it's really tasty, the lamb slow roasted, so tender. This time, the meat was cooked, but it tasted like they roasted it too quickly, so it wasn't as tender and flavorful as it has been in the past. We were there a little after 8pm, so it wasn't right at closing time. The pickles were good, the cole slaw tangy, the French onion soup, meh. Maybe it was an off night, so I'll give it another shot.</Text>

<GmapID>0x80c2c65b315cd377:0xa05d997b42357a5< /GmapID><date>1533942835542<//date>< Review>
i can't write anything here that the other reviews have not mentioned so lets cut to the chase and get down to it

must order:
-french dipped, preferred choice of meat is beef but they also have lamb as well...interesting...you also have single dipped, double dipped, or wet options, i tried double, it was just the right amount of softness in the bread, maybe i'll try wet next time..

-potato salad, in one word, amazing, one of the best i ever had that's not korean styled, although wingstop's potato salad is pretty bombed mixed with the original spicy sauce, but that's not the point, just get it, you'll know, they use whole slices of potatoes instead of chunks

-dont forget to use the spicy mustard that they give you on the table as condiment, it packs a horse's kick and will knock you off to the ground if you put too much, i like it, since i prefer wasabi

-for a 7dollar sandwich, it's definitely worth the trip, they have their own private philippe parking lot on the opposite side of the street, dont park 2 streets away like my friend Luke L and I did

-they also have a 2nd floor for more dining area, it feels like a classroom, or an abandoned laboratory though< /Review>

An L.A. original, but sadly has fallen into a typical LA hotspot, where fame has eroded quality.  After the average 20-40 minute wait, you will wait so long to receive your food that the sandwich is water logged and cold.  Its simple physics, bread dipped in hot soup will be cold and coagulated in mere minutes.  They should dip the sandwiches just prior to plating.  Very disappointing experience, try if you must, but don't have high hopes<//text>

I dislike rating this place a 2 star, But I CANNOT see paying over $ 9.00 for a smaller sandwich of selected meat that should only be worth $6 most $7.00!! <Rate>5< /Rate>< Review>
I feel like I stole Doc Brown's DeLorean and went back in time when I come here. The food and decor are basic, but well executed. Make sure you ask for your sandwich to be double-dipped, as the au jus is the best in the world. Lemonade and ice tea are only 35 cents apiece. The wait may be a long one, especially at lunch or before a Dodgers game, but your patience will be rewarded.< /Review>

<time>1213007634033< /time>< Gmap_id>
0x80c2c65b315cd377:0xa05d997b42357a5< /Gmap_id>
< review>
The American "French Dip" sandwich has been a personal favorite since I was a child -- and you don't see it offered on many menus today. Philippe the Original claims to be the originator of the French Dip -- but at least two other SoCal restaurants make the same claim... In any case, the sandwich here is yummy -- served on a freshly baked French roll dipped in "Au Jus" (pan juices). I suggest that you specify double-dipped instead of single dip since Philippe's French Dip does not come as it did when I was a kid -- served with a bowl full of the salty pan juices for dunking. Don't forget to add a slap of the molten-hot yellow mustard available at each table. It really makes this sandwich. (And the next time I visit, I'm trying the addition of blue cheese -- for a mere 80-cents.)</review>

<Date>1515472404322< /Date>< username>
Tom Wagner< /username>
<text>I'll be as concise as possible... for a change of pace: Philippe's French dip sandwiches are da bomb.  (Did I really write that?  Shame on me!).

As neither of us was feeling particularly beefish, we went with pork: she had the ham with Swiss French dip, and I had the pulled pork.  Ham is ham, but the same cannot be said about pork, and this was simply the best pulled pork sandwich I've ever had.  Delicious, satisfying, even filling without any sides, the sandwich cost a mere $6.75, a bargain by LA standards.

As for the ambiance... I happen to enjoy people who share my physique, which is based more on girth than on muscle tone.  This is good, because most of the patrons looked as though they ate at Phillipe daily, repeatedly and in vast quantities.  I happen to like sawdust on the floor as I have a habit of projectile vomiting when displeased with a meal, though it was hardly necessary this time.  The interior has an old-timey feel about it that is very appealing, especially to old farts like me.

The best part was the staff.  Most of them have been there for decades, I know thanks to Huell Howser (who commanded me in his own easy going way to eat here).  I always prefer giving my business to employees who enjoy their work, which is a big part of why we WILL be going back to Philippe.  That and the fact that the food is excellent and affordable.< /text>< Pics>
None< /Pics>

5</Rating>

<username>Jeremy Krantz</username><date>1538419007333< /date>< rate>
5</rate>
<Text>What is there to say about this place that hasn't been said in the 4,000+ reviews. Philippe's offered what had to be the best sandwiches I've ever had, all dipped in a wonderful au-jus sauce. They've been operating since 1908 and it shows in the both the style and the quality.

Bitting into those sandwiches was like a religion experience. I was there 3 times on my recent trip to Los Angeles and never got sick of it. The atmosphere is great, the long lines fade quickly with a very efficient, old-school service. And yes, I brought back a jar of mustard home with me.

It's conveniently located near Dodger stadium which makes it all the better because you can make it the eat-before-the-ballgame place. Very highly recommended!<//Text>< Pictures>

<Gmap_id>0x80c2c65b315cd377:0xa05d997b42357a5< /Gmap_id>< Review>
This place is on our must visit list every time we visit LA. The staff is always very friendly, the sandwiches and macoroni salad are delicious! I usually get a turkey dip, double dipped (they dip both pieces of bread in the au jus) sometimes with bleu cheese. I have tried the beef, turkey and lamb dips. The turkey happens to be my favorite. I also like that you can get iced tea or lemonade for about 80 cents. I highly recommend everyone try this place at least once. There is a reason they have been around forever!</Review>

zach mccall<//Name>
< Date>
1505347166780</Date>
< rating>
5<//rating>
<text>So the notorious debate between Philippe and Coles about who created the french dip seems to have been settled at least to me. While Coles does have an interesting secret "speak-easy" bar in the back in terms of actual French Dip it was overpriced, heavy and dry in my opinion.  I like my french dip wet (not an option at Coles) sort of heavy because of  the heavy pretzel baguette and also dry because the bread wasnt able to absorb the au jus. Price was $12 and seemed high for my experience.
Philippe's French Dip  seperated itself from the pack as best french dip in LA for me in these ways:
-meat choices: beef (roasted in-house daily), pork (roasted in-house daily), turkey (outsourced), lamb (roasted in-house daily), ham (roasted in-house daily).
-bread choice: wheat (baguette), white (baguette), rye (slice), sourdough (slice)
-dip choice: 1 dip, double dip, "Wet"

With all the options you can create the perfect dip for your taste...not to mention all the sides, soups (including split pea and pot roast) as well as homemade pies like boysenberry, and banana cream...so thats what really matters to me...the food...HOWEVER...if you are a purist then you are also in luck because there is verifiable evidence that Philippe's is the actual creator of the French Dip sandwich in 1908!
So there you have it, the best of both worlds,  the better sandwich, the better value  and the original...for me...Case closed! Philippe The Original is the Palace of Versailles of French Dips<//text><pictures>None<//pictures>< resp>
None</resp>

<username>Tom Wagner<//username><Time>1504454126340</Time>< rate>
5</rate>
<Review>Here is my 5 star Yelp! review:

I'll be as concise as possible... for a change of pace: Philippe's French dip sandwiches are da bomb.  (Did I really write that?  Shame on me!).

This was our first visit, even though we eat at other restaurants within a block of Philippe regularly.  It's just that when we're in Chinatown, we're usually in the mood for Chinese food.  Who woulda figured, huh?

As neither of us was feeling particularly beefish, we went with pork: she had the ham with Swiss French dip, and I had the pulled pork.  Ham is ham, but the same cannot be said about pork, and this was simply the best pulled pork sandwich I've ever had.  Delicious, satisfying, even filling without any sides, the sandwich cost a mere $6.75, a bargain by LA standards.

As for the ambiance... I happen to enjoy people who share my physique, which is based more on girth than on muscle tone.  This is good, because most of the patrons looked as though they ate at Phillipe daily, repeatedly and in vast quantities.  I happen to like sawdust on the floor as I have a habit of projectile vomiting when displeased with a meal, though it was hardly necessary this time.  The interior has an old-timey feel about it that is very appealing, especially to old farts like me.

The best part was the staff.  Today is Halloween and everyone was in costume, and they were all laughing and having a grand time.  I get the impression that this is the norm at Philippe; most of the staff has been there for decades, I know thanks to Huell Howser (who commanded me in his own easy going way to eat here).  I always prefer giving my business to employees who enjoy their work, which is a big part of why we WILL be going back to Philippe.  That and the fact that the food is excellent and affordable.< /Review><Pictures>None< /Pictures><Resp>None<//Resp>< Gmap_id>

Cynthia Staples</username>
<Review>It's everything their reputation says it is... great experience<//Review></record>
</dataset><record>
< text>
Philippe you get 3.5 stars. There was quite a bit of hype about Philippe so I finally got sucked in. Despite the Travel Channel and Philippe great history, I didn't get the WOW I was hoping for. Respect for inventing the French Dip, but the original isn't always the best. Like the Apple One computer, it sucked and all the windows based PCs dominate still until present day. I'm ashamed to say.. Yardhouse has a better French Dip. You got beat by a chain Philippe.

Don't get my wrong Philippe is good shieet it just didn't meet up to the hype. I came only to try the Beef and Pork sandwiches. After tasting my dry "double dip" style, I wanted more. Its only about 6 or 7 bucks per sandwich, but let's be realistic if you are Man Vs Food like me.. You will order at least 3 or 4 sandwiches. Raising the average price to about $18 to $24 for a grown man. Not to mention CASH ONLY! Damn you... built in 1908 today is 2010 please take plastic.

I think the best way to experience Philippe is to try it all. You have to order pie, Cole slaw, chili, apple pie, and other endless sides. Also, order a variety of drinks because there are no refills. I saw some Philippe veterans ordering beer, ice tea, and lemonade. I feel like such a rookie, but my quest was for the sandwich so maybe next time I will try the bomb looking side dishes.

I recommend Philippe to anyone that was curious. Its a great local snack. I love traditional old fashion restaurants. Sometimes you need a break from Chain restaurants. A customer on TV said, "I drove a hour for this.." You lie! I drove an hour, but it doesn't make it better. BTW the spicy mustard is bomb, but don't try it if you don't like horseradish. Try to go on a Sunday. It wasn't crowded when I went and it was easy to find parking. Close FREE parking is a miracle in LA, but a standard everywhere else.< /text>

<user_id>114629017963490151120</user_id><rate>4<//rate><user_name>Esther Kim</user_name>< pictures>

<Time>1451434066322< /Time>< Resp>
None< /Resp>
<review>Philippe The Original has been around since 1908 and is famous for their "French Dipped Sandwich." Apparently the way the sandwich came to be was by accident, but it is no accident that this is their most popular item. It relocated to its current location in Chinatown back in 1951. I had taken the metro to this location so I cannot comment on the parking situation, but like most places in Chinatown metered street parking is probably your best bet. There are always lines here, but they move fast. Pick a line, order and pay at the counter, and then wait for your food. It was pretty crowded when I went so one of my friends went and found a table while we ordered for the group.

The signature "French Dipped Sandwich" comes with a crusty French roll dipped in their own authentic "jus" created from their freshly roasted meat. For meat you can choose between roast beef, roast pork, leg of lamb, turkey, or ham. Cheese is extra and you can choose between Swiss, Cheddar, American, Monterey Jack, and Blue Cheese. The final choice you can make is whether it is "single-dip", "double-dip", or "wet". I cannot recall if I chose single-dip or double-dip, but I got their roast beef sandwich with Monterey Jack cheese. I was worried that the sandwiches here would be too overhyped for me, but I enjoyed it. It did not change my life, but it was pretty good at the time (then again, I had just run a 5K, so I was pretty hungry).

I got a side of their Potato Salad and I really liked that. If you like potato salad, I would recommend getting it here. This place is a landmark in LA and I am glad I finally got to try them... over 100 years after they first opened!</review><GmapID>0x80c2c65b315cd377:0xa05d997b42357a5<//GmapID></record></dataset><record>

Best dip sandwich French dip sandwiches Awesome food</review>

<Name>David Jimenez<//Name></record></dataset><record>
<userid>101479835485084646637</userid>< gmap_id>
0x80c2c65b315cd377:0xa05d997b42357a5<//gmap_id>
< Pics>
None</Pics>
< Rate>
4</Rate>
<Text>In the years that I have been working in South LA and sometimes driving by on my way home, I've never stopped to give this place a try. To be honest...I never even noticed this place before. And I have to admit...I've been missing out.

A friend decided that this was the place he wanted to go to to celebrate the new job he got. I personally though it was kind of strange place to want to go to, but hey, that's what he was feeling. The first thing I notice coming here was the abundance of FREE parking. For those not familiar with LA, parking can often times be an issue, so for me this was a definite plus.

The place operates more like a deli counter, you wait in line, order your items, pay and find a place to sit and munch away at your spread. The wait itself wasn't too bad, maybe 10 minutes from the back of the dinning area to the front counter.

Now, being I was in a French Dip joint, I ordered a dip sandwich. My wife and I got the Beef and Turkey respectively. She got her's with Swiss, while I got mine plain. In addition to our sandwiches, we got the cherry pie, potato salad, custard, and a pickle.

The dips were both good, but both the wifey and I preferred the beef over the turkey. The beef dip had much better taste and was much more moist, as the turkey one wasn't anything special, and the meat was slightly dry, especially considering that they reuse the wonderful juices from the meat.

On a side note, you need to use the In-House made Spicy Mustard. It's doesn't have the hot spicy flavor like chilies, but more like the burn of wasabi or horseradish. This was something that I just absolutely loved, I covered my halves of my dips in it.

The side orders didn't really have much to comment about, but the Cherry Pie was so good. The pie crust had the perfect consistency being perfectly flaky and yet still deliciously buttery. I'm looking forward to giving the other pies/desserts a try as well as the other dips....next up pork and lamb!

So for now remember to live well, but eat better!<//Text>< resp>
None</resp>

< review>
I've been in LA for over 3 years, and I've been hearing about this place forever. "The best spot" "best of LA" , they always show it on different food channels when talking about LA. Maybe my expectations were too high. I got here, went to the counter, got the roast beef sandwich, asked for fries, they dont have it, so got a potatoe salad for side. The sandwich wasn't bad, but it was far from the best sandwich i've ever eaten. It was a regular roast beef sandwich covered with steak juice. You can get a sandwich like this on any Subway, or you could go to Quizno's and get a much better sandwich than Phillipe's. The Good: cheap prices. The Bad: ordinary sandwiches, over hype, tourist trap, does not meet expectations at all.</review>

Rodney S< /Name>
<rating>2< /rating><gmapID>0x80c2c65b315cd377:0xa05d997b42357a5<//gmapID>< text>
Adam Richman, you let me down bro :(

Disgusting!

I'm not referring to the food, mind you, I'm referring to hygiene.

Lines were sorta long, but moved promptly enough.  When it was my turn, I ordered 2 beef sandwiches, 1 double-dipped & the other wet.  The worker proceeded to make my sandwiches sans gloves.  Yup, that's right.  NO gloves.  After she finished making them, she took my money, brought it over to the cashier, received the correct change, handed it to me all sans gloves.  Again, I repeat.  NO gloves.  How can this place pass county inspections when there's such a blatant violation right there?

The food itself was good.  The beef slices were very tasty & the sandwiches themselves were a tad smidgeon bigger than Arby's toasted subs.  The mustard is awesome.  It's yellow wasabi, as far as I'm concerned.  The hell with Sudafed, a lil bit of Philippe's mustard will decongest my sinuses.  Good, good stuff.

The only reason why I ate the food was because A) I was hungry & B) I wanted to see what all the hubbub was about.  Having done so, I don't see myself ever dining here again unless someone changes the food preparation.

Un-NOM Un-NOM Un-NOM</text>

<date>1433061081551</date>< rating>
4</rating>
<Review>Soon since moving to Las Vegas I haven't been to Los Angeles to much, when I met my wife we started doing Cali trips to the beach and whatnot. Wifey told me about this place as being an old school staple in LA.

Very close to Union Station and a 5 minutes walk from Olivera street (awesome street market btw). You walk in and its cafeteria-style seating, it was super crowded but we went before a Dodger game so that explained that.

So apparently you have to have the french dip, this is what there known for oh and it is the best french dip I've ever had. Make sure you bring cash, they do not take credit cards, there is an ATM machine in the store but if your like me you don't want to pay that stupid transaction fee.

The seating is quaint, never been upstairs, it is a comfortable atmosphere. If your a shy person and like your privacy this place probably isn't for you due to the close proximity of other diners. We've been back numerous times, its our lunch spot before the Dodger game. HIGHLY RECOMMENDED!!!< /Review>< Pictures>

<user_id>114461558056437807671<//user_id><user_name>Shanon Yu</user_name>< Date>
1409183402150< /Date>
<Rating>3<//Rating><Text>Old school diner best known for their french dipped sammies.

As I walked into the restaurant I immediately felt like I've been transported back into the 1950s. The whole place had an old school 50s vibe from the waitress' uniforms to the old wooden telephone booths. Since I've heard so much about this place I decided to drop by after a work meeting in Chinatown to see for myself what all the rave was about.

Unfortunately, after all the hype I have to admit that Philippe's did not meet my expectations. First off, I was quite upset that they did not accept credit card. They do have an ATM machine in the restaurant but the $2 transaction fee killed the mood. After getting my beef french dip sandwich, I noticed that they don't give you au jus on the side. I wasn't sure if this is extra but I love dipping my sammies in au jus and was quite disappointed. For the price of $7+tax, the sandwich just wasn't as filling as I had expected and if it wasn't for the spicy mustard sauce the sandwich would have tasted dry and bland. Perhaps if they knocked off a buck or two, I would then reconsider adding an additional star to their rating. Since I was still hungry I ordered a tapioca pudding ($2.67) for dessert and I still wasn't thoroughly impressed. Nothing really stood out to me. Since I heard from my coworker that the tuna melt is quite delicious here I guess I'll be trying that the next time around if I find myself dropping by again.</Text>< pics>
None</pics>
